---
const props = Astro.props;
const { data } = props;
import BeachvilleAccordionItem from "../BeachvilleAccordionItem.astro";
import BeachvilleArtistSection from "../BeachvilleArtistSection.astro";
import BeachvilleListItem from "../BeachvilleListItem.astro";
---

<div id="region-details" class="my-8" >
    
    <!-- Accordion Container -->
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto space-y-8">
            
      <!-- The Political Weather -->
      <BeachvilleAccordionItem title="The Political Weather">
        <div slot="icon">
          <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" x="0px" y="0px" width="64" height="64" viewBox="0 0 64 64" stroke="currentColor" class="w-8 h-8 text-[#064161]">
            <path d="M 29 7 C 25.686 7 23 9.686 23 13 L 15 13 C 11.686 13 9 15.686 9 19 L 9 45 C 9 48.314 11.686 51 15 51 L 49 51 C 52.314 51 55 48.314 55 45 L 55 19 C 55 15.686 52.314 13 49 13 L 41 13 C 41 9.686 38.314 7 35 7 L 29 7 z M 29 11 L 35 11 C 36.104 11 37 11.895 37 13 L 27 13 C 27 11.895 27.896 11 29 11 z M 15 17 L 49 17 C 50.105 17 51 17.895 51 19 L 51 27.328125 C 47.860304 27.865386 40.276945 29 32 29 C 23.725715 29 16.142076 27.866066 13 27.328125 L 13 19 C 13 17.895 13.895 17 15 17 z M 13 31.384766 C 15.851521 31.855688 20.994182 32.574326 27 32.865234 L 27 33 C 27 34.105 27.895 35 29 35 L 34 35 C 35.105 35 36 34.105 36 33 L 36 32.917969 C 42.43805 32.665598 47.988855 31.881828 51 31.384766 L 51 45 C 51 46.105 50.105 47 49 47 L 15 47 C 13.895 47 13 46.105 13 45 L 13 31.384766 z"></path>
            </svg>
        </div>
        <div slot="content">
          <p>
            The 1960s across Africa was a decade of independence and upheaval. Ghana, Nigeria, Kenya, Tanzania, Congo, Zambia — one after another, new nations emerged from colonial rule. The excitement of freedom was loud and joyous, but it was matched by political turbulence: coups, dictatorships, and the long shadow of apartheid in the south. Music reflected both moods — celebratory highlife filling independence parades, Congolese rumba defining nightclubs, South African jazz carrying the voice of resistance, and early experiments in new hybrid sounds hinting at what the future would hold.

          </p>
        </div>
      </BeachvilleAccordionItem>
      

      <!-- What People Were Hearing -->
      <BeachvilleAccordionItem title="What People Were Hearing">
        <div slot="icon">
          <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-[#064161]" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
            <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M9 19V6l12-3v13M9 19c0 1.105-1.343 2-3 2s-3-.895-3-2 1.343-2 3-2 3 .895 3 2zm12-3c0 1.105-1.343 2-3 2s-3-.895-3-2 1.343-2 3-2 3 .895 3 2zM9 10l12-3"></path>
          </svg>
        </div>
        <div slot="content">
          <div class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-[#064161] space-y-4">
            <!-- West Africa -->
            <BeachvilleListItem title="West Africa">
              <div slot="content">
                Highlife orchestras ruled Ghana and Nigeria — horns, guitars, and percussion bringing optimism to the dancefloor. By the end of the decade, Nigerian groups were drawing funk and jazz into their sound, setting the stage for Afrobeat. Mali’s griot traditions were electrified in bands like the Rail Band, tying folk storytelling to modern instrumentation.
              </div>
            </BeachvilleListItem>
            <!-- Central Africa -->
            <BeachvilleListItem title="Central Africa" borderColor="border-[#C13870]">
              <div slot="content">
                Congolese rumba (later soukous) was the continent’s great export. Born from Cuban son but transformed by Congolese guitarists, it was smooth, melodic, and endlessly danceable. Franco’s TPOK Jazz and Tabu Ley Rochereau’s Orchestre Afrisa International made Kinshasa the musical capital of Africa.
              </div>
            </BeachvilleListItem>
            <!-- East Africa -->
            <BeachvilleListItem title="East Africa" borderColor="border-[#FEE96A]">
              <div slot="content">
                Along the Swahili coast, taarab orchestras kept classical Arabic strings alive, while Congolese rumba spread into Kenya and Tanzania. Kenyan benga (with its fast, cyclical guitar riffs) began making its mark, setting up the 70s for explosive growth.
              </div>
            </BeachvilleListItem>
            <!-- Southern Africa -->
            <BeachvilleListItem title="Southern Africa" borderColor="border-[#C13870]"
            image={{ src: "https://syvkefpljdcoricvmqcy.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/images/africa_assets/content_images/zamrockkk.webp", alt: "Zamrock Band - Witch", width: "w-64", caption: "Zamrock Band - Witch" }}
            >
              <div slot="content">
                Apartheid-era South Africa was buzzing with township jive (mbaqanga), a danceable blend of Zulu melodies, electric basslines, and accordion riffs. Jazz musicians like Hugh Masekela and Miriam Makeba went into exile, turning local struggles into global sounds. Further north, Zambia and Zimbabwe incubated the garage-rock hybrid that would become Zamrock.
              </div>
            </BeachvilleListItem>
            <!-- Ethiopia -->
            <BeachvilleListItem title="Ethiopia" borderColor="border-[#FEE96A]"
            image={{ src: "https://syvkefpljdcoricvmqcy.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/images/africa_assets/content_images/ethio.jpeg", alt: "Ethio jazz", width: "w-64", caption: "Ethiopia" }}
            >
              <div slot="content">
                Addis Ababa’s nightlife was unlike anywhere else on the continent. Mulatu Astatke’s experiments created Ethio-jazz — modal scales, Ethiopian pentatonics, horns, organ, and a moody, psychedelic atmosphere that stood apart from highlife or rumba.
              </div>
            </BeachvilleListItem>
          </div>
          
        </div>
      </BeachvilleAccordionItem>
   
      <!-- What you can find in this playlist -->
      <BeachvilleAccordionItem title="What you can find in this playlist">
        <div slot="icon">
          <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-[#064161]" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
            <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M13 10V3L4 14h7v7l9-11h-7z"></path>
          </svg>
        </div>
        <div slot="content">
          <div class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-[#064161] space-y-4">
            <BeachvilleListItem title="West Africa – Highlife, Afrobeat Roots & Funk" borderColor="border-[#FEE96A]"
            image={{ src: "https://syvkefpljdcoricvmqcy.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/images/africa_assets/content_images/Glocal.jpeg", alt: "Glocal Highlife", width: "w-64", caption: "Glocal Highlife" }}
            >
              <div slot="content">
                Bright horns, joyous rhythms, and Afro-Latin grooves. Highlife was the sound of independence, while late-60s Nigeria saw funkier experiments that would grow into Afrobeat. Mali’s Rail Band brought griot storytelling into modern bands.
              </div>
            </BeachvilleListItem>

            <BeachvilleListItem title="Central Africa – Rumba & Soukous" borderColor="border-[#C13870]"
            image={{ src: "https://syvkefpljdcoricvmqcy.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/images/africa_assets/content_images/Rumba.avif", alt: "Rumba", width: "w-64", caption: "Rumba" }}
            >
              <div slot="content">
                Congolese rumba ruled the continent — smooth guitars, layered percussion, and Cuban-inspired grooves reimagined in African styles. By the late 60s, the pace quickened into soukous, defining nightclubs across Africa.
              </div>
            </BeachvilleListItem>
            <BeachvilleListItem title="East Africa – Benga & Taarab" borderColor="border-[#FEE96A]">
            West Africa – Highlife, Afrobeat Roots & Funk
              <div slot="content">
                Kenyan benga’s lightning guitar lines emerged, alongside the lush orchestral strings of Zanzibari taarab. Congolese rumba’s popularity spilled over into East African cities, fueling dance bands from Nairobi to Dar es Salaam.
              </div>
            </BeachvilleListItem>
            <BeachvilleListItem title="Southern Africa – Jazz, Jive & Zamrock Sparks" borderColor="border-[#C13870]">
              <div slot="content">
                South African jazz fused bebop with local rhythms, carrying messages of protest against apartheid. Township jive (mbaqanga) kept people dancing under oppression. Zambia’s youth started plugging fuzz pedals into African rhythms — the seeds of Zamrock.
              </div>
            </BeachvilleListItem>
            <BeachvilleListItem title="Ethiopia – Ethio-Jazz" borderColor="border-[#FEE96A]">
              <div slot="content">
                The smoky clubs of Addis Ababa birthed Ethio-jazz — a blend of Ethiopian scales, jazz horns, organs, and psychedelic edges. Mulatu Astatke’s sound stood apart: hypnotic, modal, and cinematic.
              </div>
            </BeachvilleListItem>
            <BeachvilleListItem title="Diaspora & Circulation" borderColor="border-[#C13870]">
              <div slot="content">
                African music didn’t stay local — Miriam Makeba sang in New York, Hugh Masekela blew his horn in exile, Congolese records spun in Paris. The sounds of the continent were already global by the late 60s.
              </div>
            </BeachvilleListItem>
          </div>
        </div>
      </BeachvilleAccordionItem>


      <!-- Technological changes -->
      <BeachvilleAccordionItem title="Technological changes">
        <div slot="icon">
          <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-[#064161]" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
            <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M9.75 17L9 20l-1 1h8l-1-1-.75-3M3 13h18M5 17h14a2 2 0 002-2V5a2 2 0 00-2-2H5a2 2 0 00-2 2v10a2 2 0 002 2z"></path>
          </svg>
        </div>
        <div slot="content">
          <div class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-[#064161] space-y-4">
            <BeachvilleListItem title="Guitars & Amplification" borderColor="border-[#FEE96A]">
              <div slot="content">
                Imported and homemade electric guitars and amps reshaped African bands. From Kinshasa’s rumba to Lusaka’s proto-Zamrock, amplification made the guitar king.
              </div>
            </BeachvilleListItem>
            <BeachvilleListItem title="Recording Studios" borderColor="border-[#C13870]">
              <div slot="content">
                National and private studios sprouted in Accra, Lagos, Kinshasa, Nairobi, Addis Ababa, and Johannesburg, documenting the sounds of a changing continent. Labels like Decca and HMV pressed African music for regional and international circulation.
              </div>
            </BeachvilleListItem>
            <BeachvilleListItem title="Radio" borderColor="border-[#FEE96A]">
              <div slot="content">
                State radio spread music across borders. A Congolese rumba hit could top charts in Kenya or Tanzania within weeks, even if the band never toured there.
              </div>
            </BeachvilleListItem>
            <BeachvilleListItem title="Reissue Culture (Later)" borderColor="border-[#C13870]">
              <div slot="content">
                Much of this music was rediscovered decades later through reissue labels (Analog Africa, Soundway, Strut, Awesome Tapes from Africa). Without them, the 60s archives of Ethiopia, Mali, Ghana, and Congo might have stayed in dusty vinyl crates. These reissues reframed African music as central to global pop history, not just regional footnotes.
              </div>
            </BeachvilleListItem>


          </div>
        </div>
      </BeachvilleAccordionItem>

      <!-- Notable Artists -->
      <BeachvilleAccordionItem title="Notable Artists">
        <div slot="icon">
          <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-[#064161]" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
            <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M16 7a4 4 0 11-8 0 4 4 0 018 0zM12 14a7 7 0 00-7 7h14a7 7 0 00-7-7z"></path>
          </svg>
        </div>
        <div slot="content">
          <div class="space-y-6">
            <BeachvilleArtistSection data={data} />
          </div>
        </div>
      </BeachvilleAccordionItem>



      </div>


</div>

<script>
  // Accordion functionality
  document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
    const accordionTriggers = document.querySelectorAll('.accordion-trigger');
    
    accordionTriggers.forEach(trigger => {
      trigger.addEventListener('click', () => {
        const accordionItem = trigger.closest('.accordion-item');
        const content = accordionItem?.querySelector('.accordion-content');
        const icon = trigger.querySelector('.accordion-icon');
        
        if (content && icon) {
          const isOpen = !content.classList.contains('hidden');
          

          
          // Toggle current accordion
          if (isOpen) {
            content.classList.add('hidden');
            icon.classList.remove('rotate-180');
          } else {
            content.classList.remove('hidden');
            icon.classList.add('rotate-180');
          }
        }
      });
    });
  });
</script>


